# 🔁 `rewrite` vs **no‑rewrite** (Vite Proxy)

## The core question this answers

> **Does the backend expect the same path the frontend uses, or a different one?**

That’s **all** `rewrite` is about.

***

## ✅ No‑rewrite (default, most common)

### ✅ What it means

*   The **frontend path is forwarded as‑is**
*   The backend **expects the same path**

```text
Browser → /api/users
Vite → https://backend.com/api/users
```

### ✅ Configuration

```ts
proxy: {
  '/api': {
    target: 'https://backend.com',
    changeOrigin: true
  }
}
```

### ✅ Example flow

Frontend:

```ts
fetch('/api/quote/v1/saveQuote');
```

Backend receives:

```text
https://backend.com/api/quote/v1/saveQuote
```

✅ Path is preserved  
✅ No surprises  
✅ Simple and safe

***

### ✅ When to use **no‑rewrite**

✔ Backend already has `/api`  
✔ API gateway prefixes endpoints with `/api`  
✔ You control frontend and backend paths  
✔ Most enterprise APIs (like yours)

📌 **Your current case falls here** ✅

***

## 🔁 Rewrite (when paths differ)

### ✅ What `rewrite` does

*   Changes the path **before** forwarding
*   Frontend and backend paths **do not match**

```text
Browser → /api/users
Vite → https://backend.com/users
```

***

### ✅ Configuration (remove `/api` prefix)

```ts
proxy: {
  '/api': {
    target: 'https://backend.com',
    changeOrigin: true,
    rewrite: path => path.replace(/^\/api/, '')
  }
}
```

***

### ✅ Example flow

Frontend:

```ts
fetch('/api/users');
```

After rewrite:

```text
/users
```

Backend receives:

```text
https://backend.com/users
```

✅ `/api` was a **frontend‑only prefix**

***

## 🧠 Mental model (remember this)

Think of `/api` like a **virtual mount point**:

| Case       | Meaning                                        |
| ---------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| No rewrite | `/api` is **real** (backend uses it)           |
| Rewrite    | `/api` is **fake** (frontend convenience only) |

***

## 🧪 Side‑by‑side comparison

### ✅ No‑rewrite

```text
Frontend URL: /api/orders
Backend URL : /api/orders
```

### 🔁 Rewrite

```text
Frontend URL: /api/orders
Backend URL : /orders
```

***

## ❌ Common mistakes (VERY important)

### ❌ Mistake #1: Using rewrite when backend already has `/api`

```ts
rewrite: path => path.replace(/^\/api/, '')
```

Backend expects:

```text
/api/quote
```

But receives:

```text
/quote   ❌ 404
```

➡️ **This is the #1 source of “proxy not working” bugs**

***

### ❌ Mistake #2: Double `/api`

```ts
target: 'https://backend.com/api'
```

Frontend:

```text
/api/users
```

Backend receives:

```text
/api/api/users ❌
```

✅ Fix: remove `/api` from **either** target or request path

***

## ✅ How to decide (simple decision tree)

Ask this question 👇

> **If I open the backend API directly, does it start with `/api`?**

### ✅ If YES

➡️ **No rewrite**

```ts
fetch('/api/...')
```

### ❌ If NO

➡️ **Use rewrite**

```ts
rewrite: path => path.replace(/^\/api/, '')
```

***

